blatt shows how Inca rulersused their Sun and Moon traditions as methods of controllingwomen and the Andean peoples the Incas conquered. She then exploresthe process by which the Spaniards employed European maleand female imageries to establish their own rule in Peru and to makenew inroads on the power of native women, particularly poor peasantwomen.Harassed economically and abused sexually, Andean womenfought back, earning in the process the Spaniards' condemnation as"witches." Fresh from the European witch hunts that damnedwomen for susceptibility to heresy and diabolic influence, Spanishclerics were predisposed to charge politically disruptive poor womenwith witchcraft. Silverblatt shows that these very accusationsprovided women with an ideology of rebellion and a method fordefending their culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aInca women. 0aIncasxSocial life and customs. 0aIndian womenzPeru. 0aIndians of South AmericazPeruxSocial life and customs. 0aSocial structurezPeruxHistory. 0aWomenzPeruxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh  aAchikee.  aAcomayo (province).  aAntisuyo.  aApurima.  aAzangaro.  aCaina (village).  aCajatambo (province).  aCapac Inti raymi.  aCapac Yupanqui.  aChoqueruntu.  aCocamama.  aDelgado, Juan.  aDias, Isidora.  aFlores, Carlos.  aFrancisca, María.  aGorgor (village).  aGualparoca.  aGuamancama.  aGuarco.  aHuamantanga (village).  aHuarcos.  aHuascar.  aHuaylla.  aIntiillapa.  aJuana Agustina.  aKramer, Heinrich.  aLlacxamisa.  aLluqui Yupanqui.  aLord Earth.  aMama Carhua.  aMarxism.  aNariguala.  aOberem, Udo.  aOtuco (village).  aPachacuti Inca.  aPachamama.  aPariahirca (mountain).  aPauquirbuxi.  aQuilla raymi.  aRaupoma.  aSañumama.  aTanta Carhua.  aTarquiurau. 